The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Subscribers to cellular service provider Airtel were unable to make or receive calls for several hours during the day on Tuesday. The situation was particularly bad in late afternoon as calls were not going through from landlines and other cellular networks. Normalcy was restored around 5.30 pm. According to N.V. Subba Rao, chief operating officer of Bharti Tele-Ventures, the disruption was a result of ?transmission related issues?, for which some cell sites in south and central Calcutta experienced congestion.

 The hearing of the case against the ban on Dwikhandita (Split in Two), Taslima Nasreen?s autobiographical work, concluded on Tuesday before a special bench in Calcutta High Court. Sujato Bhadra, convenor of the Association for Protection of Democratic Right (APDR), had initiated the case challenging the validity of the ban issued by the state government. The special bench has adjourned the verdict, reserving the right to make its decision public in the near future.

 The meeting between the five-member inquiry committee of Jadavpur University and faculty of engineering and technology students? union (Fetsu) representatives failed to arrive at a solution to the two-month stalemate on Tuesday. The committee members will meet the students again on Wednesday evening, said Manoj Mitra, dean of engineering and technology faculty and chairman of the inquiry team. He, however, said that the discussions in Tuesday?s meeting were very positive.

 In separate incidents, Krishnapada Daftari, 55, and Monohar Mondol, 70, committed suicide by hanging themselves on Tuesday in Barasat, on the northern fringes of the city. Both were suffering from prolonged illness and could not afford treatment.

 The Border Security Force, South Bengal Frontier, will organise a seminar on Friday on public interface of the BSF and human rights at National Library. Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will inaugurate the seminar.

 About 150 CPM supporters gheraoed Garden Reach police station around 11.30 pm on Monday, alleging police excess. They claimed that the police lathicharged them when they tried to meet the officer-in-charge of the police station to lodge a complaint against the assault on a CPM supporter, Manas Das, by Samajwadi Party workers. The siege was withdrawn around 2.40 am only when senior police officers intervened.

 A division bench of Justice Amit Talukdar and Justice S.P. Mitra on Tuesday granted bail to Anish Biswas, an advocate of Calcutta High Court, who was arrested 50 days ago for his alleged involvement in the Pritha Nag murder case. Pritha?s body was found inside a flat owned by a scientist of Variable Cyclotrone Energy Centre in Salt Lake under mysterious circumstances. Investigators said Anish had helped the murderers ? Pritha?s sister and brother in-law ? conceal evidence.

 A 55-year-old woman, Akbari Bibi, was killed when a private car hit her in Karaya around 2.30 am on Tuesday. Local residents rushed her to NRS Medical College and Hospital where she succumbed to her injuries. Earlier, 50-year-old Haran Das of Madhyamgram was killed when a private car hit him on Ultadanga Main Road. Local residents caught the driver and handed him over to Maniktala police. The vehicle was impounded.

